Analysis of 2019 Boston Marathon

Barbara A. Kelly

June 20th, 2021

DATASET DETAILS

This dataset is of all of the runners that participated in the 2019 Boston Marathon. The dataset contains the following runners’ information: gender, age, race hour & seconds results, their country, and rank.

Age Distribution

For age distribution, they have been divided into genders: Males and Females, with (7) seven age groups: 18-27, 28-37, 38-47, 48-57, 58-67, 68-77, 78-83. With this graphical representation, it is evident that a majority of the runners fall into the 38-47 age group for both genders. 60% of the population fall into (2) two age groups, when combined, is: 28-47.

Numerical Data of Age Distribution

The median age of the population is 53, with the total age range being between 18 and 100. The five number summary of the age range is: 18, 33, 53, 73, and 100.

The median of Male Runners: 45 years old

The median of Female Runners: 40 years old

Top 25 Countries - Other than the USA

The USA had the most participants with 71% of the population, and Canada was the second highest with a total of: 1753. United Kingdom came in third at 705 total runners, with China coming in 4th with 529 participants, and Germany at 5th with 302 participants.

Gender Distribution

The gender distribution shows as predominantly male with a total of 14,670 vs. Females totaling: 11,981. The male to female ratio is: 1.22.

Central Limit Theorem

The central limit theorem reveals that the distribution of sample means, taken from independent random samples, follows a normal distribution even if the population is not normally distributed. Using the age_range attribute in this data set the applicability of the central limit theorem can be shown. The first histogram shows the Results by Hour of with a bell-shaped curve that skews to the left. This indicates that most finished the race between the 3 and 4 hour mark.

_ The subsequent histograms are of 5 random samples of 1000 runners with results by hour - by age. So, as in the first histogram, it is easy to see with the density that most finished around the 3-4 hour mark._

Various Samples of Dataset

Taking a look at different sample sets of the data, shows various results that could be useful for future marathons. For example, of the first 6 finishers, all were male, and 5 were from Kenya, with 2nd place being an Ethiopian male. This sample set may not reveal much overall, but is of interest that the top finishers were all male under 35, and all from Africa.

The next sample was a table of all ages. This table revealed total participants per age. For example, there were 32 aged 18, 2 runners were aged 83, and more than 1000 were 45 years old. This data sample is interesting as a table, because it is clear and concise of how many runners fell into a specific age.

A quick table sample of runners 35 and younger showed that only 35% of the population fell into this age group. Also, another table to show gender as female only did not reveal anything other than the total runners of the marathon. So, the runners under 35 data could prove useful as another attribute of age, but the table to show females only would not be as beneficial.

The next sample set revealed the tail end of the overall results by participant number. Of these results, all participants were from the USA.This may not be a a useful part of the data, as it does not reveal gender or result hour. However, taking the tail end of the dataset by age, gender, and result hour, reveals all finishers were female. Their ages ranged from 33-55, with finishing times over 6 hours. One aspect that could be more useful is their country. With the above data results, we know they are all from the USA.

Another sample set took a closer look at the head values of the results by hour. This led to taking a look at the top 5 (five) results with finishers coming in at around 2:07 to 2:08. The top 5 (five) results were then compared with the last (5) five finisher’s results. These results top the 6 hour mark at 6:21 to just shy of 7 hours.

As an end result, a scatterplot was done to show age vs. result by hour. The pink dots represent females, and blue dots are male. This plot is very interesting in that it shows the density of the results overall, with outliers of both genders at hour 5+.

Results Analysis

Plotting the results by age group shows a strong pattern of longer finishing times with age group progression. However, as shown in the analysis above, age was not always the factor of finishing time.

Summary

This analysis of the 2019 Boston Marathon dataset shows that males dominated this race in both overall gender and finishing time. Females hold the tail end of finishing times with over 6 hours, coming in just under 7 hours total. While the USA had the highest race participants, they did not lead in the top finishers of the race.
